<font color="#FF0000">TRIBUTE AND HEALING</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct  8  0:43:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It was Arete (air ret Tay) that braced the Trojan Warriors.. back before Hoplite warfare, where men stood in ranks to advance on the enemy..Before Hoplite, shoulder to shoulder, warriors were more individualistic...and ancient warriors were quick to tell you how &quot;Bad To The Bone&quot; they were... my ancestors were not  much different.  Individuals went to war for honor and rites of passage etc. and were quick to boast their deeds and those of a few friends.  Individuals are not without Arete today, but it seems to be more evident in unit pride and branch of service etc.<br>
Arete gave birth to Time (Tee may), an expected adulation that returning warriors performed for... (Does it sound like acceptance is a motivator?)<br>
For my people, there was the scalp dance that Art asked about.  Women, children, relatives and friends would dance around the circle waving a scalp, taken from a formidable opponent, as tangible evidence to the taker's acts of strength, courage and ability.  Praising one's fighting men and women has been a standard practice for eons...I wonder why our society departed from such an important and meaningful display of recognition for its returning VietNam and Korean War veterans?  Could it be just one more value thrown to the ground along with sexual propriety, ethics, honesty, parenting, respect for self and others?<br>
It was a wonderful thing to have a beautiful, admiring woman to dance your scalps... but the greatest honor came when a magnificant warrior stepped forward to do the honor for a brother in arms.  We must not lose sight of the fact that nobel brothers often give us recognition and respect.. the kind that really counts!<br><br>
To My Brothers of Choice - Tatekohomni Wambli
